{"questionId":"21641","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Charlotte decides to model the shape of a cupcake to calculate its volume.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/4245581b17486dca580f995d41ea866bd7ac7821.png\"></p>\n<p>From rotating a photograph of her cupcake she estimates that its cross-section passes&nbsp;through the points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>)</mo></math>, where all units are in&nbsp;centimetres. The cross-section is symmetrical in the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis, as shown below:</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/76ffc5e524ee327e6a1ca2525800669c038d0e0b.png\"></p>\n<p>She models the section from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>)</mo></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>)</mo></math> as a straight line.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the equation of the line passing through these two points.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>7</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>625</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><br>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong> </em>for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>625</mn><mi>x</mi></math>, <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>.<br>Award a maximum of <em><strong>A0A1</strong></em> if not part of an equation.</p>\n<p><strong><br></strong><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21641","referenceCode":"21M.2.AHL.TZ1.4a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the equation of the line passing through these two points.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}